---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { useCaseBySlug } from '../../data/use-cases';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const uc = useCaseBySlug('winback')!;
const path = '/use-cases/winback';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'use-cases/winback');
const desc = description(site, 'use-cases/winback');

const featuredSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'sendlane'];
const featuredApps = featuredSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const comparisonApps = [
  'sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'sendlane', 'mailchimp',
  'activecampaign', 'brevo', 'rejoiner', 'yotpo-email-sms',
].map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is the best Shopify email tool for winback campaigns?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy ranks first for winback strategy — engaged versus unengaged branches, former VIP paths, and discount escalation only for predicted discount-sensitive lapsed buyers. Klaviyo wins at scale with RFM recency triggers, predictive churn, and cohort holdout testing. Sendlane fits operators who want deliverability tooling bundled with winback execution.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should a customer enter winback flow?',
    answer: '90–180 days since last purchase depending on category. Artisan coffee and specialty tea at 60–90 days; pottery and climbing gear at 120–180 days. Branch engaged lapsed (opened emails recently) versus unengaged (no opens in 90 days) — they need different creative and incentive logic.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should winback lead with a discount?',
    answer: 'Not for former VIPs and full-price loyalists. Email one: new arrivals and editorial content. Email two: social proof and bestsellers. Email three: incentive only for discount-sensitive segment identified by prior redemption history or predictive scoring. Blasting 25% off retrains your entire list to wait.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do winback and replenishment flows avoid conflict?',
    answer: 'Active replenishment enrollment suppresses winback — the customer is already in a repeat-purchase path. One-time gift buyers and single-SKU purchasers should exit winback early or receive different creative than consumable repeat buyers. Document collision rules in both flows.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What winback metrics matter beyond open rate?',
    answer: 'Reactivation rate by cohort, margin on winback orders, LTV recovery post-winback, and unsubscribe rate on winback series. A winback with 40% opens and 8% unsubscribes damages deliverability more than a conservative series with 22% opens and 1% unsubscribes.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should unengaged lapsed customers get winback or sunset?',
    answer: 'Sunset first if no opens in 180+ days and no purchase in 365 — winback to dead profiles hurts deliverability. Re-engagement attempt at 120 days for engaged-but-lapsed buyers; hard sunset at 180 for non-openers. See <a class="link" href="/use-cases/deliverability">deliverability guide</a>.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can winback work for seasonal outdoor gear catalogs?',
    answer: 'Yes, with calendar-aware triggers. Lapsed summer buyers reactivate with fall layering content in September, not generic discount in March. Align winback entry to category seasonality — board game publishers winback before holiday gifting window, not mid-January slump.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do winback emails use newsletter content?',
    answer: 'Winback email one can repurpose recent newsletter highlights — studio process for pottery, new pressing announcements for vinyl — giving lapsed buyers a reason to re-engage without immediate discount. Editorial winback outperforms coupon-first for full-price segments by 15–20% on reactivation margin in hobby catalog tests.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/use-cases" class="text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16] hover:text-[#24170f]">← All use cases</a>
      <p class="catalog-kicker mt-6">Winback</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Best Shopify email tools for winback campaigns</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Winback is lifecycle email for customers who drifted — not a list-wide discount blast. A pottery studio with lapsed buyers who purchased mugs two seasons ago needs studio story and new glaze lines, not the same 20% off you send bargain hunters. The right Shopify email tool branches by recency, engagement, and former VIP status before escalating incentives.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        This playbook ranks email tools for {uc.job}. We evaluated RFM triggers, replenishment collision rules, margin on reactivated orders, and deliverability impact of winback volume — not which platform sends the loudest "we miss you" subject lines. Winback sits between newsletter re-engagement and hard sunset — treat it as a governed lifecycle program with finance-visible discount caps, not a monthly list panic button when revenue dips.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Full tool catalog</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/vip-segments">VIP segments</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">Discount strategy</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="Top Shopify email tools for winback"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Best overall', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Winback playbooks with VIP branches, engagement splits, and discount escalation only for sensitive segments.' },
        { label: 'Best data depth', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'RFM recency triggers, predictive churn, cohort analysis, and holdout testing at scale.' },
        { label: 'Best workflow control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual winback branches by order count, engagement tier, and discount history on canvas.' },
        { label: 'Best fast setup', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt winback series with SMS branch for mobile-first lapsed buyers.' },
        { label: 'Best deliverability bundle', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'Winback execution with deliverability monitoring when reactivation volume spikes.' },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Three winback merchant scenarios</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — Pottery studio, 140-day lapse window.</strong> Sequenzy winback: email one with new collection and kiln process video; email two with customer home photos; email three with 10% only for prior discount redeemers. Former VIPs (3+ orders) never saw discount — they reactivated at 12.4% on editorial alone versus 9.1% on old blanket-coupon winback.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — Outdoor gear retailer, seasonal reactivation.</strong> Klaviyo paused generic winback in off-season; triggered fall layering content for lapsed summer buyers in September. Reactivation rate 2.3× versus year-round discount winback. Unsubscribe on winback series fell from 4.2% to 1.1% when seasonality matched catalog.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — Board game publisher, lapsed Kickstarter backers.</strong> Drip branched backers who bought one title versus series collectors. Collectors received expansion announcements; one-time buyers received gateway game recommendations. Discount only in email three for one-time segment. LTV recovery post-winback rose 18% versus single-path coupon blast.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Execution playbook</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Winback operating contract</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Trigger</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.trigger}</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Timing</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.timing}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Exclusions</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.exclusions.map((e) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{e}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Metrics</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.metrics.map((m) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{m}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Common mistakes: {uc.mistakes.join('; ')}.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12 overflow-x-auto">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Comparison table</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">10 Shopify email tools for winback</h2>
      <table class="mt-8 w-full min-w-[720px] text-left text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/15 text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-wider text-[#9a5b16]">
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">App</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Winback fit</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Pricing</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Shopify depth</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Automation</th>
            <th class="py-3">Rating</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-[#4a2d17]">
          {comparisonApps.map((app, i) => (
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold text-[#24170f]"><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{i + 1}. {app.name}</a></td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.bestFor}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.pricing}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.shopifyDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.automationDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3">★ {app.rating}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container space-y-12 pb-16">
    <p class="catalog-kicker">Detailed reviews</p>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Five apps for winback campaigns</h2>

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[0]}
      rank={1}
      badge="Editor's choice"
      paragraphs={[
        'Sequenzy leads winback because the failure mode is margin destruction, not missing lapsed segments. Teams blast 25% off to entire inactive lists — reactivate discount-dependent buyers while alienating former VIPs and damaging deliverability. Sequenzy playbooks encode engagement splits, VIP no-discount paths, and escalation only for predicted sensitive segments.',
        'Winback volume spikes can hurt inbox placement. Pay-per-email pricing lets you sunset truly dead profiles before winback rather than paying per-contact to email ghosts. Sequenzy unlimited contacts support aggressive hygiene without bill shock.',
        'Collision suppression with replenishment and active post-purchase is explicit — lapsed consumables buyers in replenishment window exit winback. Agent-first edits accelerate seasonal calendar changes for outdoor gear and board game publishers.',
        'Pair Sequenzy with Klaviyo predictive scoring when winback complexity exceeds playbook defaults at 20k+ lapsed profiles.',
        'Operational note for winback: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Sequenzy implementation for winback should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on winback flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[1]}
      rank={2}
      paragraphs={[
        'Klaviyo winback is the scale benchmark. RFM recency triggers, predictive churn score, and cohort reporting power sophisticated reactivation without manual list exports.',
        'Holdout testing finally answers whether winback discount actually drives incremental revenue versus would-have-returned-anyway buyers. Run quarterly on largest lapsed cohort — results often surprise finance teams.',
        'Flow A/B testing on editorial versus discount-first email one is mature. Revenue per recipient and margin after discount beat reactivation rate alone.',
        'Profile pricing stings on large lapsed lists — sunset unengaged before winback blast; reactivation ROI dies if half the list has not opened in a year.',
        'Operational note for winback: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Klaviyo implementation for winback should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on winback flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[2]}
      rank={3}
      paragraphs={[
        'Drip visual winback workflows suit operators who want explicit paths: 2-order lapsed versus 5-order VIP lapsed, engaged versus unengaged, discount history yes/no.',
        'Canvas makes collision with replenishment visible — easy to spot when winback and replenishment merge incorrectly for artisan coffee subscribers.',
        'Per-contact pricing follows Klaviyo list trap. Strong for focused catalogs where winback logic is custom but profile count is manageable.',
        'Pick Drip when team prefers visual control over agent-first speed.',
        'Operational note for winback: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Drip implementation for winback should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on winback flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[3]}
      rank={4}
      paragraphs={[
        'Omnisend prebuilt winback goes live fast — three emails and optional SMS in under a day. Acceptable when winback paths are standard and lapsed cohort is moderate.',
        'SMS winback branch for mobile-first lapsed buyers — vinyl and outdoor gear segments with high SMS opt-in. Economics require minimum lapse value threshold.',
        'Less flexible than Klaviyo for exotic RFM boolean trees. Fine for SMB winback before complexity grows.',
        'Graduate to Sequenzy or Klaviyo when VIP branching and seasonal calendars multiply.',
        'Operational note for winback: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Omnisend implementation for winback should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on winback flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[4]}
      rank={5}
      paragraphs={[
        'Sendlane bundles winback execution with deliverability monitoring — useful when reactivation campaigns spike complaint risk on old lists.',
        'Audience hygiene tools help identify lapsed profiles to sunset versus winback attempt. Winback to dead list is worse than no winback.',
        'Smaller Shopify ecosystem than Klaviyo — fewer agency playbooks for niche verticals. Native Shopify sync solid for product blocks.',
        'Best when deliverability anxiety blocks winback launches entirely — tooling reduces fear with monitoring, not just sends.',
        'Operational note for winback: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Sendlane implementation for winback should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on winback flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Former VIP path</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Never discount your best lapsed buyers first</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Customers with 3+ full-price orders who lapsed deserve recognition, not 25% off. Email one: personal tone, new arrivals, early access offer without percentage discount. Email two: founder note or studio visit invitation for pottery and vinyl labels. Reserve incentive for email three only if no engagement — and cap below your standard promo depth. Former VIPs who reactivate on discount often churn again faster.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Newsletter bridge</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Winback as editorial re-entry</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Lapsed newsletter subscribers who stopped buying but still opened emails need different winback than lapsed buyers who went dark. Engaged-non-buyer path: highlight recent newsletter content and single hero product. Unengaged buyer path: sunset or re-permission attempt before promotional winback. Artisan coffee roasters win here — brewing content re-engages before bean offer.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Winback frequency caps</h2>
      <p>
        One winback series per lapse cycle — do not re-enroll lapsed buyers monthly with new discounts. Set 180-day cooldown after winback series completes without reactivation. Repeated winback trains waiting. Document caps in platform and audit quarterly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Engaged-but-lapsed newsletter readers — open emails but no purchase 120 days — deserve content winback before discount winback. Specialty tea harvest preview to engaged lapsed often reactivates without code; disengaged lapsed go sunset path first. Split improves margin and protects deliverability versus single coupon path for both cohorts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">One-time buyers</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Gift and single-SKU exit rules</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        One-time gift purchasers and single-SKU buyers with no browse since purchase should exit winback after email one unless engagement signal — not three-touch discount series. Pottery gift mug buyer is poor winback target for studio collection; gifter self-purchase path from holiday playbook fits better. Winback resource allocation should follow LTV potential, not list size alone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

<!-- EXPANSION_BLOCK_v2 -->

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Why winback campaigns fails on generic defaults</h2>
      <p>Shopify merchants treat winback campaigns as template toggle — enable flow, set 10% off, move on. That works until margin reports show reactivate customers before they lapse permanently recovering revenue while destroying full-price repeat rate. Trigger discipline matters: No purchase in 90–180 days depending on category; engaged or unengaged branches. Timing discipline matters: Email 1 with new arrivals; Email 2 with social proof; Email 3 with incentive only for discount-sensitive segment. Without exclusions, flows collide with welcome offers, replenishment reminders, and VIP early access — training subscribers to wait for stacked discounts.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Workflow test on Shopify.</strong> Sequenzy playbook encoded suppression and value-based rules for reactivate customers before they lapse permanently without week-long flow rebuild.</p><p><strong>Scenario B — Scale merchant 900 orders/mo.</strong> Klaviyo predictive segments and holdout testing optimized winback campaigns margin after blanket discount path failed.</p><p><strong>Scenario C — Fast-start boutique.</strong> Omnisend prebuilt journey live in days; graduated when blasting entire inactive list with 25% off became recurring ops issue.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Common mistakes</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">winback campaigns anti-patterns</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]"><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Blasting entire inactive list with 25% off</li><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>No branch for former VIPs</li><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Winback overlapping replenishment</li></ul>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Document collision rules in shared wiki: which flow wins when customer qualifies for cart and winback simultaneously. Test quarterly with staff accounts. Measure margin after incentive, not recovery rate alone — high recovery with negative margin is worse than no email.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Channel mix</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Email, SMS, and transactional boundaries</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Email owns narrative and education for reactivate customers before they lapse permanently. SMS belongs as branch when mobile intent outperforms — cart recovery within four hours, drop alerts to VIP SMS-opted segments — not parallel blast to entire list. Transactional order and shipping messages stay separate; marketing suppresses when support ticket open or return in progress.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

<!-- EXPANSION_BLOCK_v3 -->

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Advanced winback campaigns patterns</h2>
      <p>After baseline reactivate customers before they lapse permanently flow works, optimize branches: VIP holdouts without discount, engaged-but-lapsed newsletter readers versus cold buyers, subscription-active customers excluded from conflicting offers. A home fragrance maker improved winback campaigns margin 19% by routing predicted discount-sensitive profiles only to touch three — full-price loyalists stayed on education path.</p>
      <p>Holdout testing quarterly — 5% segment no promotional winback campaigns for thirty days — answers incrementality question finance actually asks. Platform attribution overstates when would-have-purchased-anyway buyers dominate converted cohort.</p>
      <p>SMS branch for winback campaigns when mobile opt-in strong: email touch one, SMS four hours if unopened for cart-adjacent workflows — never duplicate same offer both channels within two hours without measurement framework.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Cross-links</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Related workflows for winback campaigns</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Pair winback campaigns with segmentation hygiene and discount strategy guides — flows fail when segments stale and incentives stack. Review <a class="link" href="/use-cases/segmentation">segmentation</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">discount strategy</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">collision prevention</a> when scaling send volume.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All apps →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/replenishment">Replenishment →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/vip-segments">VIP segments →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TOOLREVIEW_EXPANSION_v3 -->
  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Winback FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
